    <div class="elementListBrownSeparator"></div>



  <div class="friendReviews elementListBrown" >
    <div class="section">
      

<div id="review_343085540" class="review nosyndicate" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/343085540" />
    <a title="Abby" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/5233985-abby"><img alt="Abby" src="https://s.gr-assets.com/assets/nophoto/user/f_50x66-6a03a5c12233c941481992b82eea8d23.png" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/343085540?book_show_action=true">Jun 05, 2012</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Abby" class="user" itemprop="url" name="Abby" href="/user/show/5233985-abby">Abby</a>
      </span>

          added it




        

    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer343085540" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer12583622432047244998">I suppose I should let this one fade off the shelves for now, since I&apos;m not going to finish it any time soon. I read about 250 pages, and in the process wrote over 2,000 words in compulsive response. It&apos;s that kind of book.<br/><br/>Thanks to the generosity of Goodreads&apos; review section, I&apos;m not going to spare you any of those 2,000 words. You don&apos;t have to read them. It&apos;s just the kind of blather generated by a great writer.<br/><br/>When you grow up, as I did, in the United States of America, Dr. Martin Luther Kin</span>
  <span id="freeText12583622432047244998" style="display:none">I suppose I should let this one fade off the shelves for now, since I'm not going to finish it any time soon. I read about 250 pages, and in the process wrote over 2,000 words in compulsive response. It's that kind of book.<br /><br />Thanks to the generosity of Goodreads' review section, I'm not going to spare you any of those 2,000 words. You don't have to read them. It's just the kind of blather generated by a great writer.<br /><br />When you grow up, as I did, in the United States of America, Dr. Martin Luther King, Jr. seems less like a person than a FORCE OF JUSTICE. The guy has his own holiday. It comes in January, right between the holidays celebrating the first President of the nation and the one who signed away slavery. Fifty years after his death, he’s still a household name. There are those who try to mar his reputation—“He cheated on Coretta!”—but the fact remains that he’s among the few figures in history recognizable merely by his initials.<br /><br />I picked this book up as a how-to guide. After the Interfaith Leadership Institute in January, where I was trained in techniques for creating a national movement, and a visit to Memphis in the spring, I was filled with a burning question: how did they do it? How did these leaders of the Civil Rights Movement change the social and political and constitutional climate of the nation? How do you see something wrong with your society, and then change it?<br /><br />Martin Luther King has some very specific thoughts on that question. To read a lot of MLK is interesting because it lets you see, as colloquialism has it, “where he was coming from.” I see more clearly how MLK was a product of his time: he had great faith in industrialism (“the Negro” would see his economic situation improve as he left the rural setting for the factory paycheck) and technology. He took great pains to separate his ideas about labor and equality from Lenin’s ideas about labor and equality, although he doesn’t slam the Communists either. <br /><br />I am also struck by the things he doesn’t seem to think of. His treatment of gender is nonexistent: the Negro (and I am always amused at how he uses that term, as though there were only one) is a black male, a working man. He assumes the reader knows there were women who participated in the bus boycott in Montgomery, that they participated in SNCC’s lunch counter protests, and that they would reap the benefits of desegregation. Apparently this all goes without saying, and so he doesn’t mention it. He gives Rosa Parks her due, and at times he seems to make some sideways reference to working women, but by and large women hardly enter into his discussion. He does not quote them. He does not make their interests a priority or use examples from their experiences. I am not particularly uptight about these things, and I generally would say that you can hardly critique someone who lived in a particular time and place for not thinking outside the prejudices of that time and place. That takes extra effort and extra creativity, and most of us barely get by. But this is Martin Luther King we’re talking about. Simply because he thought outside the box, he sets himself up for, “But what about these disenfranchised people? And what about them? And them…”<br /> <br />I would be the last to call MLK a racist…but I think I might build a case for just that based on his writings about his trip to India. This is a very strange essay, clearly one that meant a lot to Dr. King but not one of his better remembered pieces. The experience of India was what proved to him that nonviolence could work, and he comes back to this example again and again. But he talks about India and Indians in that vaguely paternalistic, condescending tone that I often hear from middle class travelers who think they’re broadening their minds by seeing a very narrow and controlled slice of life in another place. <br /><br />And while we’re talking about people he left out, I have to say that he never mentions other minorities at all. He does not try to team up with Native Americans or various new immigrant groups that were having their own race experience in America. “The Negro” was a significant minority, a substantial population—a voting bloc. The kind of minority that can actually effect change in America’s political system if they show unity and are able to exercise their rights. This is one of the principles that undergirds MLK’s nonviolent resistance: they don’t exercise violence because it’s morally wrong, but also because their goals can be accomplished in other ways. This is part of the reason the personal charisma of MLK was so integral to the movement: to be nonviolent, you have to all pull together, and he was good at uniting the fragmented dissatisfaction of people from many class backgrounds to achieve political clout.<br /><br />As I read, I am mentally comparing the movement as MLK envisioned it (note, I don’t say the way that it was) to the way other people around the world have tried to achieve social and political change. In a time when the global economy is suffering, I see the evidence of powerful general dissatisfaction. The riots in London in the summer of 2011, for example, and even the Occupy movement and the Arab Spring. I’m not an expert in these kinds of social phenomena, and I won’t even say I know the details of these examples. But it seems to me that their underlying message is always, “Hey! Pay attention to us! We’re pissed off!” Why are we pissed off? Because times are hard. In the U.S. and U.K. in particular, they have a hard time centralizing because everybody is pissed off about something slightly different, experiencing hard times and inequality in their own way. We have no Martin Luther King to explain what we all have in common, and what to do next with all that pent-up dissatisfaction. <br /><br />And let’s think about other people bent on creating social and political change: say, Boko Haram in Nigeria, or al-Qaida, or the immolifying monks in Tibet. I am amazed, as I read MLK, at how similar some of his arguments are to theirs: “We will always be willing to talk and seek fair compromise, but we are ready to suffer when necessary and even risk our lives to become witnesses to the truth as we see it…if physical death is the price that a man must pay to free his children and his white bretheren, from a permanent death of the spirit, then nothing could be more redemptive” (p149). He bases his reasoning on morality, often explicitly religious morality, just as radical Islamicists do. He says that at some point, you must risk your own safety for the sake of what you believe and what you think the world should look like. He says sometimes, you even have to break the law. But he picks a nonviolent method—and this is important—because it’s achievable. He looked at all the options, and he believed the nonviolent one would work. So…would it work for Boko Haram? Could there be times and places where his methods don’t work? <br /><br />I’d say it’s pretty likely. I’d say there are a number of reasons, unique to his cause and historical moment, that nonviolence worked in the American Civil Rights Movement. All the same, I don’t think it has really been tried in too many other contexts. Suppose someone, perhaps another charismatic leader, took their inspiration from this thoroughly American individual the way that man took inspiration from Ghandi? They won’t have the same set of conditions to work with, by any means. But I would like to know if some of King’s ideas about the way change can happen would still work, and if they are transferrable. I like his ideas. I would like to think they still work.<br /><br />At times, though, I am amazed at how disconnected these ideas seem from what was actually happening. King knew what was happening out there—he participated in it, he suffered for it, and eventually he paid the ultimate sacrifice for it. But when you read his work, you start to associate nonviolence with warm fuzzies. It’s easy to forget that nonviolence actually feels like beatings and tear gas. In fact, it’s remarkable how much like violence nonviolence can feel. It can feel a lot like getting the shit kicked out of you and not hitting back. It’s hard, and while it makes fantastic sense intellectually, I can imagine that it makes exactly zero sense when you’re on the ground. It hurts. This is why Dr. King had to do so much explaining—this is why people had to undergo training in order to participate, and why people had to have such a very clear idea of their values going in. But doesn’t it seem just a little sick that the effectiveness of nonviolence depends on having violence used against you? King paid for it, I know—but how can he stand there and tell people that nonviolent methods are most effective when “racists resist by unleashing violence,” and therefore “Americans of conscience in the name of decency demand federal intervention and legislation.” It’s sadistic. But it worked.<br /><br />I am continually impressed at how smart this guy is. They did not give him a doctoral degree for nothing—he was an intellectual, and a smart fellow besides. I’m impressed not only by the wide variety of literature he quotes, but also the wisdom, far-sightedness and inclusiveness of his recommendations. He says the government should not just focus on fighting the Old South, but supporting the progressives. He talks about the difference between desegregation and true integration. These are not simplistic ideas about race and social justice. I sort of wonder why he is not considered a philosopher, like some of the other men who were quite explicit about the way their ideals ought to translate into social action (cough cough Marx ahem). King didn’t just have a couple of reasons—he had reasoning, and he had a rather complex rational basis on which he built his case for civil rights. Perhaps we ought not examine its logical soundness too critically. It was a practical, goal-oriented rationality, first and foremost. He thought carefully about how and why the movement should be conducted, and how to explain it to people.<br /><br />And that, I suppose, is the real magic of MLK: the fact that he could explain his ideas in a way that made sense to so many people. His writing is sophisticated enough to engage the intellectual, powerful enough to satisfy the radical, straightforward enough to ally the working class, momentous enough to get the politician’s attention. As a writer, I am duly impressed. His sentences are grammatically simple and easy to read, but they wind themselves into complex arguments. I’m well into the book and I have yet to figure out just how he does it. I must say that, as with any writer, not all his work is to quite the same standard. I tend to like his stuff from the early ‘60s best, right in the middle of his career when he really reached his stride. I am also interested to find how much material he reuses. It makes this a rather redundant read, to be honest. Once he developed his ideas, he expresses them more or less the same way over and over again. He tweaks words and sentence arrangements occasionally, and you can tell when he finally gets it just right. But often his writings use whole paragraphs from previous articles and addresses.<br /><br />If you look at his last essay, though, you see that his agenda was changing. There is much discussion about which disenfranchised group will bear the legacy of the Civil Rights Movement. Will it be gay rights? Immigrant rights? If you read Dr. King, though, he seemed to have a pretty clear idea of where his efforts would be focused after integration. He wanted to improve the situation of the poor.<br /><br />In a way, MLK was the perfect storm. He was solidly middle class, but he appealed on behalf of the poor. He was highly educated, and he agitated for better education for children. He was a Christian, a preacher no less, and he appealed to Christian values and narratives. And then, to top it all off, he became a Christian narrative himself. He was killed, Christ-like, refusing to engage in violence. A few weeks after the assassination, his last article appeared in which he wrote, “I am committed to nonviolence absolutely. I’m just not going to kill anybody, whether it’s in Vietnam or here.” Forgive them, Father; they know not what they do.<br /><br />He and his ideas came on the scene at an opportune time and for a ripe cause, as he himself acknowledges. And there are always those lingering questions, as with any martyr, of what would have happened had he lived to carry out his plans. Would he have maintained his popularity? Would he have continued in his celebrity status and prophetic role? Would he have been able to sustain the momentum of the movement? How would the movement have been different if it had continued under his leadership? It would have been very different, that’s for sure. And maybe that’s the mark of his greatness and his influence: that the history of our nation changed because he lived, and turned out differently because he died. <br /><br />I am sure that much of this has been written before, at great length, by MLK’s own personal contingent of scholars. I write about this, as I wrote about Uncle Tom’s Cabin, knowing that it’s mostly been said before. But I offer these impressions because this book made a difference to me, got me thinking, as “great literature” is supposed to do. In the end, I am very glad to have read it. I take it as one perspective on things that are still important, and will continue to be important. I will probably go in search of Malcolm X and see what he has to say on these matters, to see what reasoning counters that of MLK. Another way to make change, another smart guy, another story that’s not over.</span>
  <a data-text-id="12583622432047244998" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


      <div class="reviewFooter uitext buttons">
          

