<div id="review_3430653699" class="review nosyndicate" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/3430653699" />
    <a title="CTEP" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/116812917-ctep"><img alt="CTEP" src="https://s.gr-assets.com/assets/nophoto/user/u_50x66-632230dc9882b4352d753eedf9396530.png" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/3430653699?book_show_action=true">Jul 07, 2020</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="CTEP" class="user" itemprop="url" name="CTEP" href="/user/show/116812917-ctep">CTEP</a>
      </span>

          added it




        

          <div class="uitext greyText bookshelves">
            Shelves:
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/116812917-ctep?shelf=2016-17">2016-17</a>
          </div>
    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer3430653699" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer3006980052159642878">I had the opportunity to be a Student Today Leaders Forever bus core for Como Park Senior High School. We went to the Civil Rights Museum in Memphis, TN. I am happy that I bought the book, The Essential Writings and Speeches of Martin Luther King Jr that was edited by James M. Washington. The book contains all the writings and speeches that Dr. King made from &quot;I Have A Dream&quot; speech to the interviews &quot;Transcript of &apos;Face to Face&apos; Television News Interview&quot; in 1967. Although the book is huge and </span>
  <span id="freeText3006980052159642878" style="display:none">I had the opportunity to be a Student Today Leaders Forever bus core for Como Park Senior High School. We went to the Civil Rights Museum in Memphis, TN. I am happy that I bought the book, The Essential Writings and Speeches of Martin Luther King Jr that was edited by James M. Washington. The book contains all the writings and speeches that Dr. King made from "I Have A Dream" speech to the interviews "Transcript of 'Face to Face' Television News Interview" in 1967. Although the book is huge and contains many famous sermons, interviews, books, historical essays, and philosophy, I was only able to read enough to understand the famous nonviolent figure himself.<br /><br />Part of the book that I read about was Dr. King's philosophy. Within his philosophy he concludes that love and nonviolence are the answers. I agreed with Dr. King when he says we should be in the agape level of love: "when we love on the agape level we love men not because we like them, not because their attitudes and ways appeal to us, but because God loves them. Here we rise to the position of loving the person who does the evil deed while hating the deed he does." Most importantly, within this part of the book, it talks about his experiment and his thinking of why love and nonviolence are important to the civil right movement.He argues that God is on the side of justice, and the Civil Right Movement seeks justice, therefore God is on the side of the Civil Right Movement.<br /><br />As I read his speeches and his writing, it occurs to me that this man, Dr. King, is very well disciplined and charismatic. It makes me feel that this is the man I would look up to or even listen to in the time of adversity. It really surprised me when he talked about reading on Existentialism philosophy because I myself have read on the concept of existentialism and it helps me to see it from the eyes of Dr. King. Existentialism taught me that man and woman have the choice to create themselves, yet, they are filled with despair and angst because they are now responsible for themselves. And they live in a society where they must conform to the rules. I think Dr. King knew that he must free his people so they can live the same equality as the white men.<br /><br />This book is important to me and can relate to me within AmeriCorps because I am serving the community who continues to struggle with racism. With President Trump in charge, all my students are faced with obstacles and no opportunities. Dr. King's philosophy taught me how to love. His philosophy taught me to help those seek equal opportunities. It taught me to love even my rivals and to teach them about those who feel inferior.<br /><br />I would definitely suggest this book to my colleagues because I know that an important figure like Dr. King will be influential and will teach his ideas to my colleagues. I've seen many of my colleagues protest and by following the philosophy of Dr. King, they will be successful within their protest. </span>
  <a data-text-id="3006980052159642878" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


